There was a problem loading comments right now. Please try again later.5.0 out of 5 starsFour Complicated Stories Made EasyByAEPon June 24, 2011Format: Hardcover|Verified Purchase"Tangled Webs" is the story of four very complicated recent cases:1. Martha Stewart and the insider trading scandal;2. Scooter Libby and the Valerie Plame, CIA outing;3. Barry Bonds and steroid use in professional sports;and4. Bernie Madoff and his ponizi scheme.All four of these stories have been exhaustively covered in newspapers, magazines, on-line stories, and in television over long periods of time, which made them complicated because these venues presented pieces of the story at any given time.  When I first learned of the publication of this book, I hesitated to buy it because I am wary of most people's ability to tell a complicated story in an easy to understand fashion but I was keenly interested in the subject matter and I had faith that the author could do it based on his past writings.  The purchase was well worth it.  Mr. Stewart presented each story in an easy to understand way by taking all the pieces (people, testimony, e-mails, letters, television shows, stories, etc.) and presenting them in chronological order that no newspaper or magazine writer or television producer has been able to do.  His research is exhaustive and I finished the book knowing so much more than before I picked it up. I also walked away disappointed in not only the four main characters but in other characters and the regulatory agencies that are in existence to enforce the laws of this country.  The author asserts that lying and perjury is at an epidemic and after reading the book, I think anyone would be hard pressed not to agree.  What troubles me is (and is by no way reflective of the author but instead of the world as it is):1.  Martha Stewart should have been charged with insider trading, as should Alisa Waksul and Sam Waksul's father.2.  Karl Rove and Richard Armitage should have been charged with outing Valerie Plame, a covert CIA agent.3.  Barry Bonds and all the other professional athletes who have been taking steroids should be charged with using prohibitive substances to enhance their athletic abilities.4.  The SEC should have uncovered Madoff's ponzi scheme.The stories leave me disappointed in the subject characters but also in the characters that are holding them to the standards we call laws.0Comment|Was this review helpful to you?YesNoReport abuseCommentInsert product linkPaste the product's web address below:Product not found. Only products offered on Amazon can be linked.SelectWhat's this?What are product links?In the text of your review, you can link directly to any product offered on Amazon.com. To insert a product link, follow these steps:1. Find the product you want to reference on Amazon.com2. Copy the web address of the product3. Click Insert product link4. Paste the web address in the box5. Click Select6. Selecting the item displayed will insert text that looks like this: 
